To: Victor Miller <vmiller@ramapo.edu>
Subject: Term Project (Beta Submission)

=20

Hello Prof. Miller,

=20

I am attaching my Term Project's source code to this email.

=20

I have purposefully violated some of the coding standards for the =
following reasons:

*	Function names should start with a capital letter - Violated because =
all functions in the code start with a verb, which makes it easily =
distinguishable from a variable.
*	Function parameters should be prefixed with 'a_' - Violated because =
they reduce code readability. The functions in the source code are =
designed to be short and simple, and therefore the parameters are easily =
distinguishable from the variables. Furthermore, Visual Studio, by =
default, renders the variables names inside a function in blue and the =
arguments in grey, so it is not necessary to prefix it with 'a_'
*	Class members should be prefixed with 'm_' - Violated because they are =
prefixed with only an '_' to increase readability, and Visual Studio =
renders the member variables and functions in white (function members =
are in blue and function parameters are grey) anyway.
*	Your starter code used camelCase for variables and function names; I =
have instead used snake_case. I feel it improves readability, but I =
don't want to start a flame war over this.
*	The author name and date are removed from the class, function, and =
file descriptions because it makes more sense to use git blame.

If you feel that the code needs to strictly follow the guidelines, I =
will refactor the files and send them to you again. If you think the =
reasons are not justified, please let me know.

It is more an issue of staying with the coding standards provided by =
your company.

=20

I think I read somewhere on your website, or you probably mentioned in =
the class, that labels cannot exceed a certain number of characters, but =
I forgot the exact detail, so I am skipping any checks because it should =
not be so severe (large labels could potentially screw up the output =
when displaying the symbol table and translation, but it shouldn't be a =
big deal).

As previously mentioned, there was a limit of 10 characters for labels.  =
This is an arbitrary rule, but it is a requirement.

=20

Also, I am not sure if I need to check if the assembly source file =
contains an "ORG" statement. If the origin is not explicitly provided, =
execution starts at 0.

It theory, an assembly languages program does not need an org statement. =
 So, not need to check for one.  In reality, it should have one, because =
execution begins with the memory location 100.

=20

Please let me know if you are not satisfied with any of the liberties I =
have taken. Also, if there is anything I have missed, I would be glad to =
fix it!

=20

Thank you very much for your support!

Sorry for the extra work, but I want the class to get more of a feeling =
for the work environment in many companies.

=20

Sincerely,

Bibhu

=20

PS: Please note that the minimum required version for the compiler is =
/std:c++20 with std::format (it should be okay with VS 2022 platform =
toolset on Windows, but might not work with GNU compilers).

=20


